          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Abraham is dead",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Abraham",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "died",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Again they shew a gross want of perception and ‘do not understand His speech’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "John 8:43",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 8:43",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). They cannot discern a spiritual truth, but understand Him to be speaking of physical death. ‘My saying’ should be ‘My word’ as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "John 8:51",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 8:51",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he shall never taste of death",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] In their excitement they exaggerate His language. The metaphor ‘taste of death’ is not taken from a death-cup, but from the general idea of bitterness. It is frequent in the classics.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
