  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 52.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The Jews",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - the adverse dominant party, ready always to misunderstand his words - (then) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "said to him,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Now",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - in reference to their own charge (ver. 48), which he had solemnly disclaimed - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "we know",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "we have come to know",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐγνώκαμεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "that thou hast a daemon.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "that thou hast a daemon.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " They imply that he must be under some most bewildering hallucination. These words have scattered their momentary hesitation. They must have reasoned thus: \"He who claims such power for his own words must have personal immunity from death. This is a daemoniacal folly and delusion. There have been greater than he who heard and kept the words of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and who, nevertheless, did not escape death.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Abraham died, and the prophets",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (died); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and thou sayest, If a man keep my word, he shall never taste of death.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Here observe the wilful alteration of the Saviour's words. In place of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τὸν λόγον τὸν ἐμόν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"the word that is mine,\" they quote him as saying, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τὸν λόγον μου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"my word,\" \"the word of me\" which conveys a more personal claim; and again, in lieu of the remarkable phrase, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "οὐ θεωρήσῃ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", they say, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "οὐ μὴ γεύσηται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " equivalent to \"shall not in any way experience death\" - a form of expression incompatible with the fact of the physical death of his followers and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "fortiori",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of himself. The believer, even like the Lord, does ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "taste",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of death (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 2:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but he does not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "see",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it. The phrase, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "γεύσεται θανάτου",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is a rabbinical one for \"drinking the cup of death\" (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 18:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). John 8:52",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Now",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Looking back to John 8:48. If we were too hasty then in saying that you have a demon, your words now fully justify us. They understood Him to be speaking of natural death.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Looking back to ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "John 8:48",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". If we were too hasty then in saying that you have a demon, your words now fully justify us. They understood Him to be speaking of natural death.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Is dead (ἀπέθανε)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Better, died: referring to the historical fact.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Taste of death",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "They change the form of Jesus' statement. The Lord himself tasted of death. See Hebrews 2:9. The phrase taste of death does not occur in the Old Testament, but is common in Rabbinic writings. \"The angel of death,\" say the Rabbis, \"holdeth his sword in his hand at the bed's head, having on the end thereof three drops of gall. The sick man, spying this deadly angel, openeth his mouth with fear; and then those drops fall in, of which one killeth him, the second maketh him pale, the third rotteth.\" ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "They change the form of Jesus' statement. The Lord himself tasted of death. See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hebrews 2:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The phrase taste of death does not occur in the Old Testament, but is common in Rabbinic writings. \"The angel of death,\" say the Rabbis, \"holdeth his sword in his hand at the bed's head, having on the end thereof three drops of gall. The sick man, spying this deadly angel, openeth his mouth with fear; and then those drops fall in, of which one killeth him, the second maketh him pale, the third rotteth.\" ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
